{"actor":{"display":"Evin Tunador","id":"evintunador@gmail.com","type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":[{"text":"## Findings\n\n**1. HIGH — Capture-time secret redaction runs on the reasoning ciphertext and can silently corrupt it, unconditionally.**\n`appendEvents` (`src/store.ts:177-184`) calls `redactDraft` on **every** draft's `raw.data`, including the new `reasoningDraft` output (`src/adapters/drift.ts:70-106`), with no kind-based exemption. `redactDraft`/`walkStrings` (`src/redact/apply.ts:100-148`) deep-walks string leaves and blind-replaces any capture-tier regex match (github/openai/aws/slack/jwt/etc., `src/redact/rules.ts:27-107`) with a `[REDACTED:...]` placeholder — including inside `encrypted_content`. Capture-tier redaction is **on by default** (`captureRules`, `src/redact/config.ts:101-104`, only off if `redact.capture === false`).\n\nI reproduced this directly against the built code: feeding a synthetic `reasoning` draft whose `raw.data.payload.encrypted_content` merely *contains* a `ghp_`-shaped substring through `redactDraft(rules=capture)` mutates the stored blob (`AAAA/ghp_aaa…/BBBB` → `AAAA/[REDACTED:github-token:ba94fef94606]/BBBB`). Since real Codex ciphertext blobs are ~2-4KB of opaque base64 (per the roadmap's own estimate), a coincidental match against one of ~12 capture-tier patterns over enough turns is a real, non-hypothetical risk. This is undetectable from the outside — a reasoning event's `redactions` array looks identical whether it hit a real secret or an unlucky ciphertext byte run — and it permanently breaks the one thing this feature exists for (byte-exact replay through the provider's API). No test in the repo exercises this path (`grep -rn reasoning src/test/*.ts` outside `adapter-codex.test.ts` returns nothing).\n\n**2. MEDIUM — `cledger scan --paranoid` will flag essentially every reasoning event, and the findings can never be durably allowlisted.**\n`scanEvents` (`src/redact/scan.ts:67-104`) walks `event.raw.data` f