n as opaque\").\n\nThe test suite never catches this: `src/test/adapter-codex.test.ts:50` fixtures a reasoning payload with only `{type, encrypted_content}` — no `summary`, `id`, or `internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough` — so the mismatch between assumed and real payload shape (and the resulting fidelity loss) is untested.\n\n**2. Minor, pre-existing but relevant risk: capture-time redaction walks `raw.data` of `reasoning` events same as everything else.**\n\n`src/store.ts:180-184` runs `redactDraft` (which walks `raw.data`, `src/redact/apply.ts:144-148`) over reasoning drafts before append. Capture-tier regex rules are all anchor-prefixed (`sk-`, `ghp_`, `AKIA`, etc.) so accidental matches inside a base64 `encrypted_content` blob are unlikely, but the \"known-secrets\" exact-substring pass (`redactExtraValues`) would silently splice a `[REDACTED:...]` placeholder into the ciphertext if a previously-remembered secret literal happens to appear as a substring — silently corrupting the blob for replay purposes with no special-case warning, contradicting the \"lossless, record everything\" goal specifically for this opaque-by-design kind. This is a deliberate \"no special carve-out\" design choice per the diff, so flagging as low-severity/edge-case rather than a clear bug.","type":"text"}],"prompt":"You are an adversarial code reviewer with no prior context on this session. Your job is to find ways an implementation fails to match its stated intent — assume it's wrong until proven otherwise.\n\nRepo: /Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger (a git-notes-based CLI tool called cledger that captures coding-CLI conversations as append-only \"events\").\n\nStated intent of a just-shipped change (uncommitted, in the working tree — run `git diff` to see it): Codex's CLI writes `reasoning` response_items to its rollout transcript files. These carry provider-encrypted `encrypted_content` that only OpenAI can decrypt. The tool used to drop these outright. The new behavior: capture them as a new `reasoning`-kind event, stored opaquely (raw ciphertext preserved in `raw.data`, `content` field carries only `{opaque: true}`, never the plaintext/ciphertext itself), hidden from human-facing `cledger log`/`cledger show` output by default (revealed with `--with-reasoning`), but included by default in `cledger export` (a lossless dump command). The goal is \"record everything just in case it's useful later\" (e.g. for a sister tool to replay the ciphertext back through OpenAI's API to restore hidden reasoning) — the ledger philosophy is to lose as little real data as possible while keeping ciphertext out of human-facing views.\n\nFiles to examine: `src/schema.ts` (KNOWN_KINDS + doc comments), `src/adapters/drift.ts` (`reasoningDraft` function), `src/adapters/codex.ts` (the whole file — especially the capture loop, `convertLine`, and `sanitizeAgentMessageRaw`), `src/cli.ts` (`includeReasoning`, `hideOpaqueReasoning`, `cmdLog`, `cmdShow`, `cmdExport`). Also run `git diff` and `git log -3` to see exactly what changed and the commit message context. Also check `src/test/adapter-codex.test.ts` for what's actually tested vs not.\n\nCRITICAL: also inspect REAL Codex rollout transcript files on this machine at `~/.codex/sessions/**/rollout-*.jsonl` (there are many). Use Python or jq to extract every distinct shape of a `response_item` payload where `payload.type == \"reasoning\"` — what fields does it actually carry in practice (not just what the code assumes)? Compare that ground truth against what the code in codex.ts actually does with it. Do the same for `agent_message` payloads if any exist, and for any other response_item type you find that might carry reasoning-adjacent or encrypted content.\n\nYour specific lens: DATA FIDELITY. Look for:\n- Cases where content that should be visible/human-readable ends up hidden as \"opaque\" (or vice versa).\n- Cases where the real-world data shape doesn't match what the code assumes (extra fields, missing fields, different structure across Codex CLI versions).\n- Cases where the \"record everything\" goal is silently violated — data that's dropped, truncated, or never captured at all despite the stated intent.\n- Whether capture-time secret redaction actually processes this new opaque raw.data correctly, or whether the opacity somehow interferes with or is interfered by redaction.\n\nDo NOT look at re-anchor, forge, or unrelated CLI commands — stay focused on this one feature.\n\nReport back (under 400 words): concrete findings only, each with a file:line citation and a specific failure scenario (what real input causes what wrong behavior). If you find nothing wrong, say so plainly rather than inventing minor nitpicks.","resolvedModel":"claude-sonnet-5","status":"completed","toolStats":{"bashCount":14,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":0,"readCount":8,"searchCount":0},"totalDurationMs":196491,"totalTokens":77517,"totalToolUseCount":22,"usage":{"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2056},"cache_creation_input_tokens":2056,"cache_read_input_tokens":70867,"inference_geo":"not_available","input_tokens":2,"iterations":[{"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2056},"cache_creation_input_tokens":2056,"cache_read_input_tokens":70867,"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":4592,"type":"message"}],"output_tokens":4592,"server_tool_use":{"web_fetch_requests":0,"web_search_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","speed":"standard"}},"type":"user","userType":"external","uuid":"d1e60406-901e-4f62-97d5-47a20a3a6341","version":"2.1.217"},"format":"claude-code-jsonl/1"},"recorded_at":"2026-07-22T23:53:20.780Z","schema":"conversation-ledger/v1"}
{"actor":{"display":"Evin Tunador","id":"evintunador@gmail.com","type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":[{"text":"## Findings\n\nI reviewed the diff, `src/adapters/codex.ts`, `src/schema.ts`, `src/adapters/drift.ts`, `src/cli.ts`, and inspected 37 real rollout files under `~/.codex/sessions/**` (1503 real reasoning items) with Python, including cross-referencing parent/subagent session pairs.\n\n**1. cledger's own `redact`/`scan` pipeline can irreversibly destroy the exact ciphertext this feature exists to preserve.** `src/redact/scan.ts:99-100` calls `walkStrings(event.raw.data, ...)` unconditionally for every event kind — there is no `kind === \"reasoning\"` exemption anywhere in `scan.ts` or `redact/apply.ts` (grep confirms zero hits). The paranoid-tier `high-entropy` rule (`src/redact/rules.ts`, pattern `\\b[A-Za-z0-9+/_=-]{24,}\\b`, entropy-gated at 4.0 bits/char) will fire on essentially every real `encrypted_content` blob I checked: they're single base64url runs of ~1200-1600+ chars, all within that character class, well above the entropy threshold. Following the documented remedy (`cledger redact <id> --pattern|--all`), `redactDraft` (`apply.ts:144-148`) rewrites matched spans in `raw.data`, and the `--all` path (`store.ts:798-801,826`) deletes `raw` entirely and blanks `content`; `redactEvent` then squashes local notes history when unpushed (`store.ts:897-911`), making the original blob unrecoverable. This directly contradicts the roadmap's own claim that reasoning is \"excluded from...secret scans, which cannot scan ciphertext anyway\" (README diff) — that exclusion was never implemented.\n\n**2. Subagent/guardian rollout files collapse into the parent's `conversation.id` with colliding `seq`.** `codex.ts:326-335` overwrites `sessionId` with `session_meta.payload.session_id` whenever present — but for subagent/guardian threads, that field is the *parent's* id, not the file's own (`session_meta.payload.id`). Verified real collision: `.../rollout-...-019f7650-...c89d-....jsonl` line 8 (`message`) and `.../rollout-...-019f7711-...ce59b5a0515e.jsonl` (a \"guardian\" auto-review subagent, model `codex-auto-review`) line 8 (`reasoning`) both produce `conversation={id:\"codex:019f7650-...\", seq:8}` — unrelated content from unrelated files, same identity tuple. The file's own distinguishing id is never stored anywhere (not in `producer.session_id`, not raw — see #3), so a consumer can't tell these apart or know one came from an internal safety-review thread rather than the user's real conversation.\n\n**3. `session_meta`/`turn_context` — the only lines carrying `model`, `model_provider`, `cli_version`, `thread_source` — are dropped with zero trace.** `KNOWN_SKIPPED_LINE_TYPES` (`codex.ts:53-60`) causes these to fall through `convertLine`'s `line.type !== \"response_item\"` check with no `unrecognizedDraft` fallback (that only applies to *response_item* payload types). `reasoningDraft` (`drift.ts`) carries none of this either. No stored `reasoning` event anywhere records which model/provider/CLI-version produced it — a replay consumer has nothing in the ledger to check compatibility against.\n\n(Not a gap: `conversation.seq` = raw line index correctly preserves intra-file ordering; `internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough.turn_id` and the reasoning `id` are preserved losslessly since `raw.data` is the unmodified line; `export` always includes `raw` for every kind, no silent omission there.)","type":"text"},{"text":"agentId: af4142a7fa06faa87 (use SendMessage with to: 'af4142a7fa06faa87', summary: '<5-10 word recap>' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 93042\ntool_uses: 29\nduration_ms: 344970</usage>","type":"text"}],"tool_use_id":"toolu_014sVVYMFBSUy8mNq5PaNoEc","type":"tool_result"}],"role":"user"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","dirty_fingerprint":"7e1b3a10c505480bd4b23ac152d4c1b92e3996d0a55e63b0b41066f69c7d9501","head":"d6705ff7ea32c092c