ine; `export` always includes `raw` for every kind, no silent omission there.)","type":"text"}],"prompt":"You are an adversarial reviewer with no prior context on this session. Your job is to find ways a data schema fails to serve its stated downstream purpose — assume it's insufficient until proven otherwise.\n\nRepo: /Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger (git-notes-based CLI \"cledger\" that captures coding-CLI conversations as structured events).\n\nContext: Codex (OpenAI's coding CLI) writes conversation transcripts to local rollout-*.jsonl files. Reasoning items in those files carry a field `encrypted_content` that only OpenAI's servers can decrypt — the CLI itself never sees the plaintext. There is a companion tool called \"turnbridge\" (a sibling repo, not this one) whose job is to later \"replay\" a stored `encrypted_content` blob back through OpenAI's Responses API (as part of reconstructing/fabricating a prior conversation into a fresh Codex session, possibly on a different machine, after being round-tripped through a different CLI, or even under a different ChatGPT account than the one that originally generated it — cross-account replay was empirically verified as working by turnbridge). For that replay to work, whatever consumes cledger's stored data later needs enough information to (a) locate the right blob for the right position in a reconstructed conversation, and (b) know enough about its provenance/context to decide whether replaying it is valid/safe at all.\n\ncledger's job, per the user's explicit instruction, is ONLY to capture and losslessly store this data — NOT to build the replay logic itself (that's turnbridge's job, in a different repo you don't have access to and shouldn't assume behavior for). Your job: assess whether what cledger stores is *sufficient raw material* for such a consumer to do its job later, without cledger needing to know or care what that job's exact logic is.\n\nFirst, run `git diff` in the repo to se