(default; `src/redact/config.ts:101-104`), walking `raw.data` string leaves with no kind-based carve-out. A false-positive match of any capture rule (github/openai/aws/jwt token-prefix patterns, `src/redact/rules.ts:27-107`) inside the encrypted_content string would rewrite that span to `[REDACTED:...]`, permanently mangling the blob before it's ever stored — `eventId` doesn't cover `raw` so this wouldn't even change the event's id. High-entropy near-random ciphertext is precisely the content class most likely to accidentally match a fixed literal-prefix pattern (vs. normal prose/code), and this is new: this kind guarantees 100% of its `raw.data` is such content, unlike other kinds where it's incidental.\n\n**3. (Plausible, unverified) Same-seq id collision on file rewrite.** `content` is always the constant `{opaque:true}`; identity reduces to `session_id + occurred_at + conversation.seq` (`src/schema.ts:130-144`). `occurred_at` falls back to a session-constant `baseTime` when a line lacks its own timestamp (`src/adapters/codex.ts:354`, `104-116`). If Codex's rollout file is ever rewritten/compacted in place (the `\"compacted\"` line type at `codex.ts:53-60` suggests this happens) such that a genuinely different reasoning item lands at a previously-used line index with the same fallback timestamp, the new blob would collide with and be silently dropped as a \"dedup\" of the old one. Not proven — depends on whether real Codex reasoning lines always carry per-line timestamps (the test fixture assumes they do) and whether rollout rewriting is truly in-place — but untested by the shipped suite either way.\n\n**4. Minor:** `docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md` (not touched by this diff) still states reasoning payloads are \"skipped, not stored, and never reconstructed\" and \"never preserved\" — now false, and could mislead a future reader/maintainer (e.g. turnbridge).","type":"text"},{"text":"agentId: a93dbad2b3977214e (use SendMessage with to: 'a93dbad2b3977214e', summary: '